#!/bin/sh
# pre-commit: the deterministic gate. Not advisory.
#
# WHY THIS EXISTS: on 2026-07-16 Claude built the verify gate, wrote memory
# entries calling it "the done-gate", argued through a long session that a
# deterministic gate plus a human are the only real green light, and then made
# five commits without running it once. Not by defiance: each skip had a
# defensible-sounding reason ("verify does not cover scripts/"). Advisory gates
# lose to rationalization, every time, including from the author of the gate.
# So this one does not ask.
#
# TOOL-AGNOSTIC ON PURPOSE. A PreToolUse hook only sees the tool it is wired to.
# The same day, a PowerShell call walked straight through a guard that only
# checked Bash. git runs this hook itself, no matter which shell invoked git, so
# switching tools does not route around it.
#
# --no-verify skips this hook. That flag is BLOCKED in
# ~/.claude/hooks/pretool-guards.js (GATE_BYPASS), so the two layers cover each
# other's gap.
#
# ACTIVATION (local config, not tracked, so a fresh clone must run it):
#   git config core.hooksPath .githooks
# This file lives in .githooks/ rather than .git/hooks/ so that it is version
# controlled: weakening the gate shows up in a diff a human reads, instead of
# happening silently.
#
# KNOWN LIMIT, stated rather than hidden: this verifies the WORKING TREE, not the
# staged subset. If you stage part of your changes, the gate still tests
# everything on disk. That is stricter than a commit needs, never looser, so it
# does not create false confidence.

set -e
echo "[pre-commit] deterministic gate: npm run verify"
npm run verify

# Second gate: every reviewer finding must be fixed, or dismissed with a written
# reason. Blocks the silent drop. It does not judge whether a reason is GOOD (that
# needs judgment); it guarantees the reason exists, is attributable, and gets
# printed here for a human to overrule.
echo "[pre-commit] review gate: findings must be dispositioned"
node scripts/review-gate.js

# Third gate: if a plan is APPROVED and therefore being enforced, the commit must
# stay inside its scope and its done-steps must cite evidence that really exists.
# No approved plan means this is a no-op, by the human's decision on 2026-07-20:
# blocking all work whenever no plan exists would be an outage, not a gate.
echo "[pre-commit] plan gate: scope + step evidence"
node scripts/plan-check.js

echo "[pre-commit] gate passed."
